        content: "Congressional Debate simulates the legislative process, combining public speaking with parliamentary procedure. It's unique among debate formats for its large-group structure.\n\n**Key Characteristics:**\n• **Large group format:** 10-25 students debate together as a 'chamber'\n• **Legislation focus:** Debaters propose and debate actual bills and resolutions\n• **Parliamentary procedure:** Uses motions, points of order, and formal rules\n• **Individual speeches:** Each debater gives speeches on multiple pieces of legislation\n• **Presiding officer:** Students take turns running the chamber\n\n**How It Works:**\nStudents write or are assigned legislation to debate. The chamber votes on what to discuss, then debaters give speeches for or against each item. A student presiding officer manages procedure.\n\n**Skills Developed:**\n• Legislative process understanding\n• Formal parliamentary procedure\n• Adaptability across multiple topics\n• Extemporaneous speaking\n\n**Who Thrives in Congress?**\nFuture politicians, those interested in how government works, and debaters who enjoy variety within a single competition. If you like the idea of debating many topics in one session and learning legislative procedure, Congressional is compelling.",
