        content: "What makes LD unique is its focus on values rather than policies. While Policy debate asks 'What should we do?' LD asks 'What should we believe?' or 'What matters most?'\n\n**The Value Structure:**\nEvery LD case is built around a **value**—an abstract principle the debater believes is most important. Common values include:\n• Justice\n• Morality\n• Freedom\n• Human dignity\n• Democracy\n• Security\n\n**The Value Criterion:**\nBeneath the value sits a **criterion**—the standard for measuring whether the value is achieved. For example:\n• Value: Justice\n• Criterion: Protecting individual rights\n\nThe criterion tells the judge how to weigh arguments. If protecting rights achieves justice, then whichever side better protects rights should win.\n\n**Philosophical Depth:**\nLD debaters engage with major philosophical traditions:\n• Kantian ethics (duty-based morality)\n• Utilitarianism (greatest good for greatest number)\n• Social contract theory\n• Natural rights philosophy\n• Virtue ethics\n\nThis philosophical grounding gives LD debates intellectual depth that many debaters find deeply satisfying.",
