        content: "The Affirmative speaks first and defends the resolution. This position comes with specific strategic considerations.\n\n**Affirmative Advantages:**\n• Set the terms of the debate with your framework\n• Force the Negative to respond to your case\n• Speak both first and last (AC and 2AR)\n• Can anticipate common Negative arguments\n\n**Building the AC:**\nA strong Affirmative Constructive includes:\n• **Framework:** Value and criterion that favor the resolution\n• **Definitions:** Clarify key terms in the resolution\n• **Contentions:** 2-3 main arguments proving the resolution\n• **Impacts:** Why your arguments matter\n\n**Throughout the Round:**\nThe Affirmative must:\n• Defend their case against attacks (1AR, 2AR)\n• Attack the Negative case (1AR, 2AR)\n• Maintain offensive and defensive balance\n• Use the final speech to crystallize\n\n**Strategic Considerations:**\n• Don't make your case too complex—you need to defend it\n• Prepare responses to common Negative positions\n• The 2AR should identify clear voting issues\n• Time allocation matters: don't spend too long on weak arguments",
