        content: "Policy Debate's most distinctive feature is its year-long topic. While other formats change topics monthly or bi-monthly, Policy uses one resolution for the entire school year.\n\n**Example Resolution:**\n'Resolved: The United States federal government should substantially increase its protection of water resources in the United States.'\n\n**What Year-Long Topics Mean:**\n• **Extraordinary depth:** You can research every aspect of water policy thoroughly\n• **Cumulative knowledge:** Everything you learn carries forward\n• **Strategic complexity:** Arguments evolve as the year progresses\n• **Evidence arms race:** Teams constantly update files with new evidence\n\n**How Topics Work:**\nThe resolution is broad enough to allow many different 'affirmative cases' (specific plans). Teams might advocate:\n• Increasing EPA water quality regulations\n• Expanding wetlands protection\n• Reforming agricultural runoff policies\n• Improving infrastructure for clean water access\n\nNegative teams must be prepared to respond to any case that falls under the resolution.\n\n**Annual Cycle:**\n• New topic released in summer\n• Initial research over summer/early fall\n• Strategies develop as tournaments occur\n• Arguments become more refined throughout the year\n• By season end, debaters know the topic deeply",
