        title: "The Plan: Affirmative's Policy Proposal",
        content: "In Policy Debate, the Affirmative team doesn't just defend an abstract principle—they propose a specific **plan** of action.\n\n**What is a Plan?**\nA plan is a detailed policy proposal that the Affirmative claims the federal government should adopt. It specifies:\n• What action will be taken\n• Which agency will implement it\n• How it will be funded\n• When it will take effect\n• What enforcement mechanisms exist\n\n**Example Plan:**\n'The USFG should substantially increase Clean Water Act enforcement by:\n1. Mandating EPA inspections of all industrial facilities annually\n2. Increasing penalties for violations by 200%\n3. Funding through an industry fee system\n4. Implementation to begin within 12 months'\n\n**Why Plans Matter:**\n• Creates a specific target for Negative attacks\n• Forces Affirmative to defend real-world feasibility\n• Allows detailed comparison of policy options\n• Teaches real policy analysis skills\n\n**Building a Strong Case:**\nAffirmatives must prove:\n• **Inherency:** Why current policy won't solve the problem\n• **Significance:** The problem matters\n• **Solvency:** The plan actually works\n• **Advantages:** Benefits outweigh costs",
