        content: "Policy Debate is legendarily research-intensive. Understanding what this means is crucial before you commit.\n\n**What Research Looks Like:**\n• Reading academic journals, think tank reports, government documents\n• Finding specific evidence supporting your arguments\n• Creating 'cut cards'—quoted evidence ready to read in rounds\n• Organizing thousands of pieces of evidence into accessible files\n• Constantly updating with new publications\n\n**Evidence Standards:**\nEvidence must include:\n• Full citation (author, publication, date, page)\n• Highlighted/underlined portions (what you'll read aloud)\n• Enough context to verify the quote is accurate\n\n**File Organization:**\nTeams organize evidence by:\n• Affirmative cases (each plan they might run)\n• Disadvantages (each DA with links, impacts, answers)\n• Counterplans (various alternatives)\n• Topicality arguments (definitions, standards)\n• Answers to common arguments\n\n**The Reality:**\n• Serious Policy teams accumulate thousands of pages of evidence\n• Research is ongoing throughout the season\n• Teams share evidence through trading and open-source databases\n• Top programs have extensive research support\n\nThis intensity isn't for everyone, but those who embrace it develop extraordinary research skills.",
