        type: "content",
        title: "What Judges Evaluate",
        content: "Policy judges evaluate rounds holistically, but focus on key elements:\n\n**The Affirmative Must Prove:**\n• **Inherency:** The problem won't be solved without the plan\n• **Significance:** The problem matters enough to act\n• **Solvency:** The plan actually solves the problem\n• **Advantages outweigh:** Benefits exceed costs/risks\n\n**The Negative Can Win By:**\n• Defeating any of the 'stock issues' above\n• Proving disadvantages outweigh advantages\n• Showing the counterplan is better than the plan\n• Winning topicality (plan doesn't fit resolution)\n• Winning a kritik (fundamental objection)\n\n**Judging Paradigms:**\nDifferent judges have different philosophies:\n• **Tabula rasa:** Judge as blank slate, decide based on arguments made\n• **Policymaker:** Evaluate which policy is best\n• **Stock issues:** Affirmative must prove all stock issues\n• **Kritik-friendly:** Receptive to philosophical challenges\n\n**Adapting to Judges:**\nGood debaters learn judge preferences and adapt accordingly.",
