        content: "PF was specifically designed to be accessible to 'lay' judges—those without debate expertise.\n\n**What This Means:**\n• Avoid technical jargon and debate-specific terms\n• Speak at conversational pace (no spreading!)\n• Arguments should make sense to any intelligent adult\n• Persuasion matters as much as technical debate skills\n\n**Communication Style:**\n• Use clear, everyday language\n• Explain the significance of your arguments\n• Tell compelling stories with your evidence\n• Make eye contact and connect with judges\n\n**Why This Design Choice?**\nPF was created partly in response to Policy's perceived inaccessibility:\n• Parents and community members could judge\n• Students developed real-world communication skills\n• Debates resembled public discourse more closely\n\n**Strategic Implications:**\n• You can't win by overwhelming opponents with speed\n• Quality of argument matters more than quantity\n• How you say something matters as much as what you say\n• Likeability and credibility factor into persuasion\n\n**The Reality:**\nSome PF circuits have become more technical, but the format's core principle remains: win by being more persuasive to a general audience.",
