        content: "PF's Crossfire periods are unlike cross-examination in other formats. They're meant to resemble natural dialogue.\n\n**How Crossfire Works:**\n• Both speakers ask AND answer questions\n• Either debater can ask or respond at any time\n• More conversational than formal cross-ex\n• The first question goes to the speaker who just finished\n\n**Crossfire Goals:**\n• Clarify opponent's arguments\n• Point out contradictions or weaknesses\n• Set up arguments for later speeches\n• Show the judge you understand the issues\n\n**Crossfire Tips:**\n• Be respectful but assertive\n• Don't let opponents dominate the time\n• Ask pointed questions that help your case\n• Answer questions honestly but strategically\n• Keep it conversational—judges dislike aggression\n\n**Grand Crossfire Strategy:**\n• All four speakers participate\n• Coordinate with your partner—don't interrupt each other\n• Use this to highlight your strongest points\n• It's right before Final Focus—set up your ending\n\nGood Crossfire makes you look reasonable and knowledgeable; bad Crossfire makes you look defensive or aggressive.",
