        content: "A Public Forum case must be persuasive, clear, and well-evidenced. Here's how to build one:\n\n**Framework (Optional):**\nSome PF cases begin with a framework—the lens through which the judge should evaluate the round. This might be:\n• Prioritizing economic impacts\n• Focusing on humanitarian considerations\n• Weighing short-term vs. long-term effects\n\n**Contentions:**\nThe heart of your case. Typically 2-3 contentions, each including:\n• **Claim:** What you're arguing\n• **Warrant:** Why your claim is true\n• **Evidence:** Source-backed support\n• **Impact:** Why this matters\n\n**Example Contention:**\n**Claim:** Universal basic income would reduce poverty.\n**Warrant:** Direct cash transfers address immediate needs more efficiently than bureaucratic programs.\n**Evidence:** Studies from pilot programs in Finland and Alaska show significant poverty reduction.\n**Impact:** Millions of families would achieve financial stability.\n\n**Evidence Standards:**\n• Cite source, author, and date\n• Read key quotes verbatim\n• Explain what the evidence proves\n• Be prepared to show the full source if challenged",
